05746nam a22007215i 9780813542485DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20032003nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135424857 a10.36019/97808135424852doi  a(DE-B1597)529665  a(OCoLC)609837409  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a296.834109731 aKaplan, Dana Evan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerican Reform Judaism :bAn Introduction /cDana Evan Kaplan. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. A Historical Overview -- tChapter 2. An Introduction to Reform Jewish Belief -- tChapter 3. The Evolution of American Reform Theology -- tChapter 4. The Reform Revolution of the 1990s -- tChapter 5. The Worship Revolution in the Synagogue -- tChapter 6. The Struggle for Recognition in the State of Israel -- tChapter 7. New Challenges in Reform Jewish Education -- tChapter 8. The Outreach Campaign -- tChapter 9. The Struggle for Women’s Equality -- tChapter 10. The Acceptance of Gays and Lesbians -- tChapter 11. The Battle over the Future of Reform Judaism -- tChapter 12. Where Do We Go from Here? -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe only comprehensive and up-to-date look at Reform Judaism, this book analyzes the forces currently challenging the Reform movement, now the largest Jewish denomination in the United States. To distinguish itself from Orthodox and Conservative Judaism, the Reform movement tries to be an egalitarian, open, and innovative version of the faith true to the spirit of the tradition but nonetheless fully compatible with modern secular life. Promoting itself in this way, Reform Judaism has been tremendously successful in recruiting a variety of people—intermarried families, feminists, gays and lesbians, and interracial families among others—who resist more traditional forms of worship. As an unintended result of this success, the movement now struggles with an identity crisis brought on by its liberal theology, which teaches that each Jew is free to practice Judaism more or less as he or she pleases. In the absence of the authority that comes from a theology based on a commanding, all-powerful God, can Reform Judaism continue to thrive? Can it be broadly inclusive and still be uniquely and authentically Jewish? Taking this question as his point of departure, Dana Evan Kaplan provides a broad overview of the American Reform movement and its history, theology, and politics. He then takes a hard look at the challenges the movement faces as it attempts to reinvent itself in the new millennium. In so doing, Kaplan gives the reader a sense of where Reform Judaism has come from, where it stands on the major issues, and where it may be going. Addressing the issues that have confronted the movement—including the ordination of women, acceptance of homosexuality, the problem of assimilation, the question of rabbinic officiation at intermarriages, the struggle for acceptance in Israel, and Jewish education and others—Kaplan sheds light on the connection between Reform ideology and cultural realities. He unflinchingly, yet optimistically, assesses the movement’s future and cautions that stormy weather may be ahead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aJewszUnited StatesxIdentity. 0aJewszUnited StatesxSocial life and customs. 0aJudaismy20th century. 0aReform JudaismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asocial science, jewish studies, jew, jud